comment text: Yoi will have to look at the anal plates. So hindi pwede na from afar, malalaman na na venomous or not. Unless you can identify. Sa Pilipinas, cobra and king cobra, kraits and coral snakes ang nakakatigil ng puso. While pit vipers cause necrosis. Those are the ones that are highly venomous. So kailangan mo lang e-identify ang habitat at pagkain nila and then learn to identify the snakes. Pero kung palatandaan whether venomous or not, the only way is the anal plates. So thay means dapat alam paano e-handle ang ahas para makita ang anal plates. So the best method is to learn how to identify the venomous snakes and their juveniles too.

post text: In light of recent snake bites i would like to offer some info. One - if you stay 5 m away from any snake you are safe. Most people get bitten when they attack a snake. Imagine you have a stick of 1 m in your hand and the snake is 4 m long. The snake can strike 1/3rd of its length, so that is more than 1 m, longer than your stick. So avoid attacking the snake. Observe it, so you can see where it moves away and then call a expert to assist if snake needs to be removed. Take a picture from 5 m away is a good idea. If we can identify the snake as non venomous or non dangerous not including pythons (dangerous) at least you dont need to panic so much. Imagine a expert can see it's a harmless rat snake and not a King Cobra like you were thinking, you can save a lot of stress. Many non dangerous snakes is among us and they control the rats. Now if you get bitten - Do not wait for help unless your only way to go to hospital is to run or walk yourself, then wait as movement will spread venom faster into the body etc. If transport is available go immediate to any hospital that has a trauma unit (important) Without a trauma unit is like getting a aspirin for cancer treatment it wont help you and you will only waist precious time. Most serious bites in PH is neuron toxin, meaning your brain signal to tell your lungs to breath gets blocked by the venom so you need a trauma unit (breathing apparatus) to help you breath until antivenom arrive. On the way remove anything like rings on fingers, watches, bracelets, anything that will be difficult to remove when the body parts swell up. Keep the bite area beneath the heart as a position so you use gravity to slow down movement of venom into the body. Dont cut/suck/ burn/apply anything over the wound. If water is close by rinse the area with water quickly. Same as venom in eyes in case of spitting cobra, rinse eyes 20 to 30 minutes with running water only. Put your head under the tap and rinse your eyes as water is running. Then go to any clinic that can inspect and apply best eye drops and observation. No antivenom is needed for venom in eyes. Venom in the mouth from spitting cobra is not a high risk factor unless you have open cuts in your mouth as venom is a protein that gets broken down in the tummy. For any bite - Time is the most important factor here. Get to hospital with Trauma unit immediately. As soon as any symptoms appear treatment should start and dont panic if you dont know what snake bite you as we treat the symptoms. Sometimes you can have a dry bite(snake did not inject venom) from a venomous snake then you dont want to use anti-venom as it is not without it's own risk. Thank you for your attention until here.

Ivan Velasco you are wrong. You need to check your information. Naja ph. range stops somewhere south of Manila. The "tail" of Luzon is samar cobra range. This is important to know, because some harmless shrub snakes have yellow patterns similar to samars, and that is not a mistake you want to make. Samars have a very large range, across multiple islands and really shouldn't be named that. They take the name from the island they were first observed and described on - it does not mean that they are only found on Samar. Hope that helps. Any admin can verify this, but also so can Google searches.
